🧠 Core Idea (Intuition First)

You are given a hidden permutation of:

{4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42}

You can ask:

? i j → returns a[i] * a[j]

👉 Goal: Find the full permutation using ≤ 4 queries.

💡 Key Observation

All numbers are distinct and small.

👉 That means:

If you know the product of two numbers, you can uniquely determine the pair.

Example:

4 × 8 = 32 → only possible pair is (4,8)
15 × 16 = 240 → only possible pair is (15,16)

👉 So product → unique pair mapping exists.

⚡ Strategy Overview

We divide array into two parts:

First half → indices (1,2,3)
Second half → indices (4,5,6)

We solve each part using 2 queries.

🧩 APPROACH 1: Brute Thinking with Set (Your First Code)
🔍 Idea

We query:

x12 = a1 * a2
x13 = a1 * a3

Now try to find a1.

💡 Key Trick

If a number x is:

divisor of x12 → possible a1
divisor of x13 → possible a1

Then:

a1 = x
a2 = x12 / x
a3 = x13 / x
🧠 Why it works?

Because:

x12 = a1 * a2
x13 = a1 * a3

👉 Common element = a1

⚙️ Steps
Step 1: Find a1, a2, a3

Loop over all values in {4,8,15,16,23,42}:

Check if divides both x12 and x13
Check if resulting numbers are valid
Step 2: Remove used numbers

Now remaining set has 3 elements.

Step 3: Repeat same logic

For:

x45 = a4 * a5
x46 = a4 * a6
🧾 Code (Approach 1)
void solve() {
    set<int> st = {4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42};
    vector<int> ans(6);

    cout << "? 1 2" << endl;
    cout.flush();
    int x12; cin >> x12;

    cout << "? 1 3" << endl;
    cout.flush();
    int x13; cin >> x13;

    int a1 = -1;

    for (auto x : st) {
        if (x12 % x == 0 && x13 % x == 0) {
            int a2 = x12 / x;
            int a3 = x13 / x;

            if (st.count(a2) && st.count(a3) && a2 != x && a3 != x) {
                ans[0] = x;
                ans[1] = a2;
                ans[2] = a3;
                a1 = x;
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    st.erase(ans[0]);
    st.erase(ans[1]);
    st.erase(ans[2]);

    cout << "? 4 5" << endl;
    cout.flush();
    int x45; cin >> x45;

    cout << "? 4 6" << endl;
    cout.flush();
    int x46; cin >> x46;

    for (auto x : st) {
        if (x45 % x == 0 && x46 % x == 0) {
            int a5 = x45 / x;
            int a6 = x46 / x;

            if (st.count(a5) && st.count(a6)) {
                ans[3] = x;
                ans[4] = a5;
                ans[5] = a6;
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    cout << "! ";
    for (auto x : ans) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl;
    cout.flush();
}
🧩 APPROACH 2: Precompute Mapping (Clean + Smart)

This is the best and most elegant solution 💯

🔍 Idea

Precompute:

product → (a, b)

Example:

32 → (4,8)
120 → (8,15)
...
⚡ Why this is powerful?

Now when you query:

? 1 2 → gives product

👉 You instantly know the pair!

💡 Trick

Query:

(1,2) → gives pair (a,b)
(2,3) → gives pair (b,c)

👉 Common element = a[2]

🧠 Functions
1. common(a, b)

Find common element between two pairs.

2. other(pair, x)

Return the other element.

⚙️ Steps
Step 1:
p1 = product of (1,2)
p2 = product of (2,3)

Find:

a2 = common(p1, p2)
a1 = other(p1, a2)
a3 = other(p2, a2)
Step 2:

Same for (4,5,6)

🧾 Code (Approach 2 - BEST)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int query(int i, int j) {
    cout << "? " << i + 1 << " " << j + 1 << endl;
    int x;
    cin >> x;
    return x;
}

int common(pair<int,int> a, pair<int,int> b) {
    if (a.first == b.first || a.first == b.second)
        return a.first;
    return a.second;
}

int other(pair<int,int> p, int x) {
    return (p.first == x ? p.second : p.first);
}

void solve() {
    vector<int> arr = {4, 8, 15, 16, 23, 42};

    map<int, pair<int,int>> mp;

    for (int i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
        for (int j = i + 1; j < 6; j++) {
            mp[arr[i] * arr[j]] = {arr[i], arr[j]};
        }
    }

    vector<int> ans(6);

    auto p1 = mp[query(0,1)];
    auto p2 = mp[query(1,2)];

    ans[1] = common(p1, p2);
    ans[0] = other(p1, ans[1]);
    ans[2] = other(p2, ans[1]);

    p1 = mp[query(3,4)];
    p2 = mp[query(4,5)];

    ans[4] = common(p1, p2);
    ans[3] = other(p1, ans[4]);
    ans[5] = other(p2, ans[4]);

    cout << "! ";
    for (int x : ans) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl;
}
